Project Report¶

Introduction¶

YouTube's streaming platform displays a list of top trending videos which changes constantly based on a combination of various factors. Our project is meant to find patterns and relations between variables to draw conclusions and give suggestions to youtubers. Content creators with the goal of a trending video can find useful tips and suggestions based on our analysis of various YouTube metrics. The suggestions include the best topics and tags, publishing times, and metrics to increase their video popularity and success.

The questions we attempted to answer in our project were:\ How can youtubers tag their videos to improve their videos and what pattern they can learn from the tags from the trending video list?\ How can youtubers design the titles of video to attract more views and increase the chance of trending?\ When should a youtuber publish a video to get more views and get the videos trend faster?\ How impactful are user interactions on the success of videos?\ Which user interaction created the most trending videos? \ How does having comments disabled affect the views a video gets? How about having ratings disabled?\

For the first question, we believe that tags that are used in the videos can help youtubers to know what topic and types of video are more popular. We can provide suggestions to the youtubers from the tags analysis about their topic design and contents chosen for the video.

For our second question we wanted to know what aspects of a title would make a video more appealing and increase its popularity and likelihood of being on the top trending list. We will analyze our data to get the common length of the title, and also the popular words these trending videos will use to attract viewers.

For the third question, we have the assumption that publishing time would interfere with the speed of the video to get trending. To estimate at what period there are more audiences and at what time a video published will certainly have more viewers and trends faster than other videos.

For our fourth question we want to see the impact that each user interaction has on metrics used to measure a video's success such as engagement and impression. We also want to get a better understanding of the correlation between user interactions and how they play a role in whether a video makes the top trending list or not.

For our fifth question we wanted a better understanding of which user interaction is used as a metric within the algorithm that puts videos on the top ten trending list.

For our sixth question we wanted to know if disabling user interactions such as comments and ratings will positively or negatively affect the success of a video. Also if disabling these user interactions will lead to a positive or negative correlation with other user interactions such as views.

The answers to these questions matter because they can help content creators on YouTube use the algorithm that determines which videos make the top trending list to their advantage. This will increase the variety of content that is on the top trending list. As well as increase awareness of the video and the creators page which can increase monetization of their channel.

The dataset we analyzed is the daily record from the top 200 trending YouTube videos in the US region. The data was collected between November 14th, 2017 and June 14th, 2018 with missing dates of January 10-11th and April 7-13th of 2018. The dataset is from https://www.kaggle.com/datasnaek/youtube-new.

Choice for Heavier Grading on Data Processing or Data Analysis¶

We choose to have heavier grading on the data analysis section because we believe that in this part, we demonstrate greater proficiency in a broader scope. We would like our project to be more heavily graded on data analysis because we believe our analyses regarding the variables that impact the success of a video goes above and beyond basic data analysis. Our data analysis seeks to understand the YouTube platform and trending algorithm from the perspective of the primary players, youtubers and users. In our data analysis we go in depth on how youtubers can be successful and have their videos put on the top trending list based on efforts on both sides. We have done deep analyses on each side and have created suggestions based on our findings.

Data Processing¶

Some of the datas such as 'views', 'likes', 'dislikes', 'comment_count' are well formarted and we can use them directly in future analysis. Other columns must be cleaned accordingly

One of our research questions uses the publish time of videos column which was not properly formatted. To fix it, we converted the values in 'publish_time' into a datetime object in the form of 'year-month-day hour:minute:second' and split it up into two new columns, 'publish_date' and 'publish_time'. We applied this same process to 'trending_date'.

In [4]:

df['publish_time2']=pd.to_datetime(df['publish_time']).dt.time
df["trending_date"]=pd.to_datetime(df['trending_date'], format='%y.%d.%m')

Next, we used bins by binning publishing time into four periods of time (midnight to 6 being night, 6am-12pm being morning, 12pm-18pm being afternoon, and 18pm to midnight being evening) and identifying them as night, morning, afternoon and evening. By doing so, we give more meaning to publishing time so that we can use more statistical approaches on the data.

'Tags' is the most informative and extensive part of the dateset. It represents the keywords and tags that each trending Youtube video is identified by in their search algorithm. To process the data, we first wipe off unnecessary punctuations to make the tags more easy to read. Then we create a list of all tags and count them, forming a result that includes all tags by all videos.

Since we already have the list of all tags, we can get the top 20 tags that have the largest frequencies. This shows the structure of what we can do on the tags with further conditions on other variables in the final report, such as given months, channel, category etc.

The number of tags are evenly distributed before 30 and dramatically decrease after 30. The mean for the number of tags are 19.7. We can suggest that youtubers can include whatever number of tags they want, but are better to include no more than 30 tags in the videos.

In [21]:
# find all popular tags for each month 
#loop through 12 months
for x in range(1,13):
    df_month=df2[pd.to_datetime(df2['trending_date']).dt.month==x]
    #df_month['tags']=df_month['tags'].str.replace('\"|\[none\]','')
    #
    tags=[]
    for i in df_month.index:
        tags=tags+df_month['tags'][i].split("|")
    tags_result=pd.Series(tags).value_counts()
    df_eachmonth=pd.DataFrame(tags_result)
    df_eachmonth=df_eachmonth.reset_index()
    df_eachmonth=df_eachmonth.drop(columns=[0])
    #df_eachmonth.columns=x
    if x==1:
        df_month_tags=df_eachmonth
    else:
        df_month_tags=pd.concat([df_month_tags,df_eachmonth], axis=1, ignore_index=True)
df_month_tags.columns=['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
df_month_tags=df_month_tags.drop(columns=['Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct'])

# find all popular Titles for each month 
for x in range(1,13):
    df_month=df2[pd.to_datetime(df2['trending_date']).dt.month==x]

    titles=[]
    for i in df_month.index:
        key=[]
        key+=word_tokenize(df2['title'][i])
        key_words=[]
        for i in range(len(key)):
            key_words=key_words+(re.findall('[a-zA-Z]+',key[i]))
        titles=titles+key_words

    titles = [word for word in titles if word not in stopwords.words('english') and word != 'vs' and word !='ft' and word !='n' ]
    lmtzr = WordNetLemmatizer()
    titles = [lmtzr.lemmatize(word) for word in titles]
    titles_result=pd.Series(titles).value_counts()
    df_eachmonth=pd.DataFrame(titles_result)
    df_eachmonth=df_eachmonth.reset_index()
    df_eachmonth=df_eachmonth.drop(columns=[0])

    if x==1:
        df_month_titles=df_eachmonth
    else:
        df_month_titles=pd.concat([df_month_titles,df_eachmonth], axis=1, ignore_index=True)
df_month_titles.columns=['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
df_month_titles=df_month_titles.drop(columns=['Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct'])
df_month_titles.head(20)

Time-series Analysis¶

The ARIMA(Auto Regressive Integrated Moving Average) is a widely used statistical method for time-series data forecasting. In this part we are developing an ARIMA model for time series to look at how ‘likes’ is changing over the publish time and to generate a prediction. By doing this, it provides the youtubers probable suggestion on when to publish their video could receive more likes. The model mainly used the algorithm from Python library statsmodels.

In [27]:
dft=df[["publish_time","likes"]]
dft=dft[dft.publish_time>=pd.to_datetime("2017-12-01")]
In [28]:
dft1=dft.groupby('publish_time')['likes'].mean()
dft2=dft.groupby('publish_time')['likes'].mean().astype(np.float64).resample('D').mean()

Step 1: First look

The data is plotted as a time-series with the month along the x-axis and the likes on the y-axis. Stationarity of series is an important prerequisite for modeling. We can see that the likes has a clear trend and the mean is changing over time so our series is not stationary, which will require differencing to make it stationary.

In [29]:
dft2.plot(figsize=(12,8))
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.25, 0.5))
plt.title("Likes")
sns.despine()

Step 2: First Differences

We then take a first differences of the data and we can now see that the series is stationary. It took one difference to make our series stationary, so we can decide that we have an ARIMA(AR, 1, MA).

In [30]:
dft3= dft2.diff(1)
plt.figure()
plt.plot(dft3)
plt.title("1st Order Differencing")
plt.show()

Step 3: Interpreting ACF(Autocorrelation function) and PACF(Partial Autocorrelation function) plots

Looking at the ACF and PACF function can give us a idea what models to fit. The ACF shows a tapering pattern and has a non-zero values (1) at first and the rest of the values remain close to 0.2 and shows a tapering pattern. PACF has a non-zero values (1) at first and the rest of the values remain close to 0 and shows a tapering pattern. Since the model contains both the AR and MA model, we are able to adjust the parameters and find the ideal one.

In [31]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf
acf = plot_acf(dft2, lags=30)
plt.title("ACF")
acf.show()
pacf = plot_pacf(dft2, lags=30)
plt.title("PACF")
pacf.show()

Step 4: ARIMA model

According to the above results, we are using ARIMA(1,1,1) to run the model. The P-value should be less than 0.05 and in our case the p-value is highly insignificant. Therefore our model output is not outstanding enough. The model should get trained multiple times in order to get the optimal ARIMA model, which could be our future goal. For now we are moving to the visualization part.

User Interaction¶

User Interaction is a big part of monetizing a youtube channel, so creators are generally very interested in trying to maximize it. In the 3 analyses below we consider which user interactions are most strongly correlated with high performing videos, the expectations for trending youtube videos over time and whether interactions are a necessary condition for trending videos.

How impactful are user interactions on the success of videos?¶

From the cleaned dataframe we have taken the user interactions and rating for each video to determine the correlation between each and the user interaction correlation with the rating that the video received. The correlation table shows that likes and views are positively correlated to ratings. This shows us that the amount of likes and views a video receives is a contributes to the algorithm that puts a video in the top ten trending list.

The scatterplot above is used to visually show the correlation amongst the user interactions and specifically how they correlate with metrics such as impressions and engagement used by YouTube to measure how well a video has done. Overall, based on the scatterplot impressions is highly postively correlated with views as well as likes. While engagement is highly positively correlated with like

We focused on 3 different smaller scatterplots within the larger one that stood out to us as interesting or statistically significant

The graph that shows the correlation between likes and views shows us that there are some videos that get a lot of views per like but after that it models nicely into two different categories of videos with many likes: some videos get tons of views and likes at the same time and some videos get tons of likes but fewer views. This might help us understand the like counter on viral videos.

We then looked at dislikes versus views. Most videos end up acquiring many views without acquiring that many dislikes, having a high ratio of views to dislikes. There are a couple of different possibilities, as in two other tracks the videos can trend in. Widely disliked content seem to follow one of two slopes, as seen from the graph. A content creator could use this graph to track the dislike ratio on their most viewed videos to see which slop pattern it is following. A creator could attempt to predict how many dislikes they're going to get in total throughout the lifespan of the video.

Finally, we loked at the graph describing what the ratio of likes to dislikes is going to be. It doesn't show how big the video is, but rather how well receieved it is. A high dislike to like ratio on videos may get a lot of views, as seen in the scatterplot of views to dislikes where there are two separate slopes that follow such a trend. But if that happens to your videos you may want to consider creating content that is more ad friendly and well received as the youtube algorithm as well as ad sponsors may be hesitant to support controversial creators. To look further into Like ratio and examine this question a little more, we wanted to look at whether or not popular trending videos had a different like to dislike ratio as compared to all other videos on youtube.

To determine which user interaction put videos on the top trending list we took the averages of each user interaction and displayed the amount over time that the data consists of. We can make this inference because of the comparison between lines in the graph which are the different interactions. As well as that videos have been put on the list over time have also had an increase in the amount of views.

Based on views consistenly being the highest form of user interaction we make the assumption that this interaction is used as a metric for the algorithm to put videos on the top trending list.

How does having comments disabled affect the views a video gets? How about having ratings disabled?¶

The analysis above examines how user interactions affect trending videos. A natural question then is if user interactions themselves are even important to examine. To do this we look at the two videos with limited interaction, comments disabled and ratings disabled videos, and look at whether or not they come out with a lot of views.

In [40]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2)

sns.boxplot(x="comments_disabled", y="views", data=df, ax=axs[0])
#use logscale for y in order to actually be able to see data
axs[0].set_yscale("log")

sns.boxplot(x="ratings_disabled", y="views", data=df, ax=axs[1])
#use logscale for y in order to actually be able to see data
axs[1].set_yscale("log")

Videos with comments disabled seem to statistically have very similar view counts as videos with comments enabled. This runs against common sense, which would tell you that disabling commments would give you fewer views but this does not actually seem to be the case. While the interquartile range for videos with comments disabled (True box) is slightly larger than the other, this difference is probably not statistically significant given the difference in sample size. The sample size for comments disabled is obviously much smaller than videos that do not have comments disabled. Therefore any diparity in the box plots is likely just noise and not signal.

We repeat the analysis from above and come to the same conclusion for videos that have ratings disabled: any small difference in interquartile ranges seem to be statistically insignificant. View distribution seems to be independent of ratings or comments being disabled. This suggests that while the analysis might help us model how user interactions correlate with trending videos, videos without user interaction seem to perform similarly as a group. This in turn suggests that top trending videos don't necessarily require user interaction for high view count; even with zero interaction videos can still do well.

Conclusions¶

Generally, we designed the project to focus on two aspects within the YouTube platform. One aspect being the youtuber/content creator side and the other being the user side of the platform. For the content creator side we focused our analysis on tags, titles and time series.

From analyzing the tags, we provide suggestions for youtubers about topic design and content chosen. We suggest youtubers to use clear nouns with simple adjectives to describe the video content and keep the number within 20. About the topic choice based on tags, youtubers should focus on more holidays like christmas or major events like new movies as their topics because these tags show high popularity in trending videos. Similarly, analyzing the title gives youtubers a general idea of how to design the length, keywords and pattern of the video title. In the title analysis, we suggest youtubers to use more strong and attractive words to get more view attention from viewers. They should also keep the title between 6 and 12 words. We also run a time-series model using ARIMA to look at how ‘likes’ is changing over the publish time. From the above data analysis we can give youtubers suggestions for improving click volume and audience engagement.

For the user side of the platform we focused our analysis on how much of an impact user interaction has on a video’s success. We looked at the correlation between user interactions and their correlation among YouTube metrics such as impressions and engagement. Based on our analysis of these correlations we would suggest for a content creator to focus on user interactions such as views, likes and comments to not only increase their popularity but also to increase their metrics within YouTube. In addition to analyzing the correlation amongst user interactions we also analyzed the interactions themselves to get a better understanding of which user interaction is most likely to get a video on the top trending list. Based on our analysis we determined that the user interaction that plays a significant role in whether a video makes the top trending list or not is views. We suggest for youtubers to focus their marketing and engagement efforts on views if they wish for their video to make the top trending list. Lastly based on our analysis of user interaction features being disabled we can conclude that ratings and comments do not impact the amount of views a video gets. This tells us that if a youtuber decided to disable comments and ratings they can still have a successful video and make the top trending list. Overall, our project has analyzed the data of YouTube videos that have made the top trending list. We have done various analyses to solve the algorithm and determine the various variables that play a role in the success of a video. From our project which included data processing and analysis we can conclude and suggest various tactics and strategies that youtubers can use to get their video on the top trending list on YouTube.
